# UCI Heart Disease dataset (all four sites):
# https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/45/heart+disease
url <- "https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/heart-disease/processed.cleveland.data"

col_names <- c("age","sex","cp","trestbps","chol","fbs","restecg",
               "thalach","exang","oldpeak","slope","ca","thal","num")

# Cleveland only
cleveland_raw <- read.csv(
  url, header = FALSE, col.names = col_names, na.strings = "?"
)

# All four sites combined
sites <- c(
  "https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/heart-disease/processed.cleveland.data",
  "https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/heart-disease/processed.hungarian.data",
  "https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/heart-disease/processed.switzerland.data",
  "https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/heart-disease/processed.va.data"
)

all_raw <- map_dfr(sites, ~ {
  read.csv(.x, header = FALSE, col.names = col_names, na.strings = "?")
})

# Cleaning helper
clean_heart <- function(df) {
  df %>%
    mutate(
      heart_disease = if_else(num > 0, 1L, 0L),
      chol     = if_else(chol    <= 0, NA_real_, as.numeric(chol)),
      trestbps = if_else(trestbps <= 0, NA_real_, as.numeric(trestbps))
    ) %>%
    select(heart_disease, chol, age, trestbps) %>%
    drop_na()
}

heart_cle <- clean_heart(cleveland_raw)   # n = 303
heart_all <- clean_heart(all_raw)         # n = 675

# Exploration / confirmation split (Cleveland only, 70/30)
set.seed(203)
n_cle   <- nrow(heart_cle)
exp_idx <- sample(seq_len(n_cle), size = floor(0.30 * n_cle))

heart_explore <- heart_cle[ exp_idx, ]
heart_confirm <- heart_cle[-exp_idx, ]   # confirmation set used in all results
```

```{r models, include=FALSE}
# Models (confirmation set for Cleveland; full set for all-sites)
model1_cle <- lm(heart_disease ~ chol,                    data = heart_confirm)
model2_cle <- lm(heart_disease ~ chol + age + trestbps,   data = heart_confirm)
model1_all <- lm(heart_disease ~ chol,                    data = heart_all)
model2_all <- lm(heart_disease ~ chol + age + trestbps,   data = heart_all)

# Heteroskedasticity-robust (HC3) standard errors
se1_cle <- sqrt(diag(vcovHC(model1_cle, type = "HC3")))
se2_cle <- sqrt(diag(vcovHC(model2_cle, type = "HC3")))
se1_all <- sqrt(diag(vcovHC(model1_all, type = "HC3")))
se2_all <- sqrt(diag(vcovHC(model2_all, type = "HC3")))
```

## Introduction

Heart disease is one of the top causes of death in the USA, being responsible for around one in five deaths per year. Serum cholesterol has been regarded as the most important contributor, yet recent research suggests this perception does not fully represent the complexity of the problem — specifically, the association becomes much weaker when controlling for age and blood pressure (Wilson et al., 1998; Detrano et al., 1989). Such knowledge is relevant for policy makers, healthcare professionals, and epidemiologists alike, and if the association is found to be very weak after these adjustments, there is a need to reconsider the current approach.

This leads to the research question: *"How strongly does serum cholesterol act as a predictor for heart disease, after controlling for age and resting blood pressure?"* We aim to outline the joint distribution of these variables without trying to establish a causal mechanism or create a deployable predictor.

## Data

We use the UCI Heart Disease dataset (Janosi et al., 1988), which collects patient records from four hospitals: the Cleveland Clinic Foundation, the Hungarian Institute of Cardiology, the V.A. Medical Center in Long Beach, and the University Hospital in Zurich. As Cleveland's records are the most complete and have been the benchmark for most prior work in this space, they serve as our main dataset ($n = 304$ before cleaning). We also run our core analyses on all four sites combined ($n = 920$ before cleaning) to see if the patterns we find in Cleveland hold up more generally. Each record in the data corresponds to one patient visit, covering demographics, resting clinical measurements, and angiographic findings. Heart disease diagnosis is based on the \texttt{num} variable, which originally ranges from 0 to 4 depending on the severity of vessel narrowing. We collapse this into a simple yes/no indicator, which is 1 for any narrowing and 0 for none, following the convention established in earlier studies.

**Operationalization.** Our primary predictor *X* is \texttt{chol}, serum cholesterol measured in mg/dL from a fasting blood draw. Our outcome *Y* is the binary heart disease indicator described above. We include \texttt{age} (in years) and \texttt{trestbps} (resting blood pressure in mmHg) as covariates in our adjusted models. Observations with missing or physiologically implausible cholesterol values (coded as \texttt{?} or 0) and missing blood pressure values are excluded, leaving $n = 303$ for the Cleveland analysis and $n = 675$ for the pooled four-site dataset after applying the same filters.

To guard against overfitting our modeling choices to the data, we split the Cleveland dataset 70/30 into exploration and confirmation sets. All decisions about variable selection and operationalization were made using only the 30\% exploration set. Every number reported in this document — summaries, coefficients, and p-values alike — comes from the 70\% **confirmation set** ($n = `r nrow(heart_confirm)`$).

**Limitations.** The binary outcome does not capture severity of disease. A linear probability model can produce predicted values outside $[0, 1]$, though this is rarely extreme in practice. The dataset is a clinical convenience sample of higher-risk patients referred for angiography, meaning the heart disease rate ($\sim$47\%) is much higher than in the general population; estimates should not be applied to broader prevalence.

