Figure 1 makes the core finding visual. The left panel shows nearly identical cholesterol distributions for patients with and without heart disease — the interquartile ranges overlap almost entirely, and neither group clusters at a distinctly higher level. The right panel reinforces this: three lines representing low, median, and high cholesterol levels are nearly indistinguishable from one another across the full age range. Age, by contrast, drives a steep increase in predicted probability regardless of cholesterol level. Together, the two panels show that cholesterol adds little to our description of who has heart disease once age is known.

## Model Specification

We estimate four linear probability models, organized by dataset (Cleveland confirmation set vs. all four sites) and by covariate set (cholesterol alone vs. cholesterol plus age and resting blood pressure):

- **Model 1 (Cleveland):** $\widehat{\text{HD}} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot \text{chol}$
- **Model 2 (Cleveland):** $\widehat{\text{HD}} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot \text{chol} + \beta_2 \cdot \text{age} + \beta_3 \cdot \text{trestbps}$
- **Models 3–4:** same specifications estimated on the four-site pooled dataset.

We use a linear probability model (LPM) rather than logistic regression because coefficient interpretation is more direct for a descriptive goal: each $\hat{\beta}$ gives the average percentage-point change in heart-disease probability associated with a one-unit increase in the predictor. All reported standard errors are heteroskedasticity-robust (HC3), which is appropriate because binary outcomes mechanically produce non-constant variance.

We considered adding a cholesterol-squared term to capture potential non-linearity, but the residuals-vs-fitted plot (Appendix) shows no systematic curvature, so the linear specification is retained. We also considered log-transforming cholesterol given mild right-skew, but the substantive interpretation did not change and the linear scale is more intuitive for a clinical audience.

