**2. Model Specifications Tried.**

| Specification | What We Learned |
|---|---|
| `heart_disease ~ chol` (Cleveland) | Baseline; chol coefficient positive but not significant ($p \approx 0.26$) |
| `heart_disease ~ chol + age + trestbps` (Cleveland) | Adding age drives $R^2$ up; chol becomes smaller and still insignificant |
| `heart_disease ~ chol` (All four sites) | Larger $n$ makes chol significant, but effect size unchanged |
| `heart_disease ~ chol + age + trestbps` (All four sites) | Both age and BP now significant; chol marginally significant |
| `heart_disease ~ log(chol) + age + trestbps` | Log transform did not improve residual pattern or interpretation; dropped |
| `heart_disease ~ chol + I(chol^2) + age + trestbps` | Squared term not significant; residuals showed no curvature; dropped |

**3. Residuals vs. Fitted Values Plot.**

```{r resid-plot, fig.cap="Residuals vs. fitted values for Model 2 (cholesterol + age + resting BP). Left: Cleveland confirmation set. Right: All four sites. The orange loess smoother tracks near zero with no systematic curvature, supporting the linear CEF assumption.", fig.width=7, fig.height=2.8}

make_resid <- function(model, title) {
  df <- data.frame(
    fitted    = fitted(model),
    residuals = residuals(model)
  )
  ggplot(df, aes(x = fitted, y = residuals)) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.18, color = "steelblue", size = 0.9) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", color = "darkred", linewidth = 0.5) +
    geom_smooth(se = FALSE, color = "darkorange", linewidth = 0.75, method = "loess") +
    labs(title = title,
         x = "Fitted Values", y = "Residuals") +
    theme_minimal(base_size = 9) +
    theme(
      plot.title       = element_text(size = 9, face = "bold"),
      panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
    )
}

resid_cle <- make_resid(model2_cle, "Cleveland Only")
resid_all <- make_resid(model2_all, "All Four Sites")

resid_cle + resid_all
```

